[normal]Written evidence submitted[bold] by Professor David Heald[bold] (FTF 13)[bold]&#xa0;[bold]the [bold]implications [bold]for public spending [bold]of [bold]fixed-term parliaments[bold]&#xa0;[bold]a)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]the vast information advantage possessed by the Executive
[normal];
[normal]b)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]the 
[normal]well-established practice
[normal] of leaking and planting that precede
[normal]s
[normal] most Budget, Autumn Statement and Spending Review announcements, 
[normal]which
[normal] function as distracters
[normal];
[normal]c)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]the gaming of rules, such as treating Private Finance 
[normal]Initiative (PFI) 
[normal]projects as off-balance sheet
[normal], arbitraging boundaries between general government and public sector and between public sector and private sector, and redefining the length of the economic cycle in order to satisfy a fiscal rule
[normal];
[normal]d)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]the degeneration of formal Parliamentary financial procedures into mechanical processes that are largely treated as irrelevant
[normal]; and
[normal]e)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]the over-stretched remit of the Treasury Committee 
[normal]having the result that 
[normal]it does not function as a 
[normal]‘Spending and Tax
[normal] Committee
[normal]’
[normal], 
[normal]which would be 
[normal]explicitly and continuously focused on 
[normal]spending and 
[normal]tax
[normal].
[normal]There are some connections to other questions, particularly the interaction between fixed-term Parliaments and coalit
[normal]ion government. Moreover, this M
[normal]emorandum shows how the present conjuncture might lead to improved scrutiny by Parliament of the public finances.
[normal]a)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]the question of how many years a Spending Review will cover and the extent to which it projects forward into the following Parliament
[normal]; and
[normal]b)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]the 
[normal]question of how frequently Spending Reviews are held: the initial practice of every two years (1998, 2000, 2002 and 2004) chan
[normal]ged to every three (2007, 2010 and 
[normal]2013), but there must be one in 2015
[normal].
[normal]With the probable length
[normal] of the Parliament known to all, the dynamics 
[normal]of frequency and duration 
[normal]are likely to change. 
[normal]For example, a Government elected in 2015 might opt in 2015 for a Spending 
[normal]Review covering four years (
[normal]2016-17, 2017-18
[normal],
[normal] 2018-19
[normal] and 2019-20
[normal]), planning 
[normal]to hold
[normal] a further Spending Review in 2019 in advance of the 2020 election. Whether there 
[normal]is a
[normal] majority or coalition government after 2015 seems likely to be an important factor. 
[normal]a)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]After 1997, the Labour Government re
[normal]-
[normal]launched the 
[normal]PFI
[normal] as Public-Private Partnerships (PPP), vastly expanding the scale
[normal] 
[normal]and – thro
[normal]ugh arbitraging FRS 5A (ASB, 1998
[normal]) 
[normal]by 
[normal]Treasury Technical Note 1 (Revised)
[normal] 
[normal](Treasury Taskforce, 1999)
[normal] –
[normal] kept the capital costs and borrowing out of the spending and borrowing numbers (Heald and Georgiou, 2011a)
[normal];
[normal] 
[normal]b)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The status of Network Rail was design-engineered to ensure that, whatever the financial reporting treatment, its borrowing would be outside the national accounts numbers
[normal];
[normal] 
[normal]c)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The 1997-2010 
[normal]Labour 
[normal]Government kept its election promises not to increase the basic or higher rate of income tax, instead increasing National Insurance Contributions
[normal], thereby exploiting the low level of public understanding of the UK tax system
[normal];
[normal]d)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The 1997-2010 Labour Government redefined the economic cycle in order that it notionally complied with 
[normal]the
[normal] 1998 fiscal rules
[normal]; 
[normal]e)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The Coalition Government has committed to buying electricity output from the EDF-
[normal]planned 
[normal]Hinkley Point 
[normal]C 
[normal]nuclear power station at 
[normal]a strike price 
[normal]roughly double the
[normal] current market price
[normal]; and
[normal]f)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The Chancellor of the Exchequer has recently suggested an above-inflation rise in the minimum wage (
[normal]Parker et al, 2014
[normal]).
[normal] 
[normal]Answers to this question are necessarily speculative because the fixed-term is new and this is the first coalition since 19
[normal]45
[normal]. 
[normal]T
[normal]he divergent electoral interests of the Coalition parties suggests that little 
[normal]planning 
[normal]will be done publicly, though the Treasury is likely to be doing its own preparations. An ‘End of Parliament Fiscal Report’ on the New Zealand model would 
[normal]be a valuable innovation, though political parties expecting to gain an overall majority might lack enthusiasm. Such a document would improve understanding of the fiscal problems likely to confront an incoming government. 
[normal]A practical question is whether the preparation of this document would be the responsibility of the Treasury or the Office for Budget Responsibility (OBR), or divided between them. In New Zealand, where there is no OBR or Fiscal Council, the Treasury prepares the document which is published in the name of the Minister of Finance
[normal] (English, 2011
[normal]; Parliamentary Counsel Office, 2005
[normal])
[normal].
[normal]If there were currently a majority Government, my hunch is that the 2013 Spending Revie
[normal]w would have 
[normal]covered more years than 2015-16.
[normal] Again, providing that there were a majority Government, a 2015 Spending Review would then cover the four years to the 2020 election.  It is possible that the Treasury wanted the 2010 Spending Review to cover four years, though 
[normal]it is 
[normal]understandable that, in the novel circumstances of a coalition, three years was the maximum thought achievable.
[normal] 
[normal]Accordingly, the answer to the direct question is that there is scope for the year coverage to be linked to the Parliamentary term. Whether this would happen depends on political calculations: a majority Government would feel obliged to go into an election with costed forward plans (a huge institutional advantage over opposition
[normal] parties
[normal]) whereas a minority coalition 
[normal]party 
[normal]and the O
[normal]pposition would be wary of being locked into numbers after the election.
[normal]3 February
[normal] 2014
