[normal] The frequency of Spending Reviews and the number of years covered are separate questions. A Spending Review every two years has had three years of plans, with the third year of one becoming the first year of the next. There must be a Spending Review in 2015 because the existing plans stop at 2015-16.
[normal] This is ‘probable’ because Oppositions, which repeatedly challenge governments to call an election, would find it 
[normal]difficult to deny a dissolution
[normal] to the Prime Minister
[normal].
[normal] Until November 2008, the then Conservative Opposition 
[normal]had 
[normal]accepted the public expenditure plans of the then Labour Government
[normal] (Lea, 2008)
[normal].
[normal] Such arbitrage bred a huge ‘advice industry’, in reality providing cover for off-balance sheet treatment.
[normal]  Under European System of Accounts 2010
[normal],
[normal] operational from 
[normal]1 September 
[normal]2014, Network Rail 
[normal]will be re
[normal]classified to the public sector. 
[normal]  
[normal]Whatever the merits of particular values for the minimum wage, it should be recognised that this is an example of using law and regulation instead of tax and spending.
[normal] 
[normal]Lienert (2013) examined how constraints on legislators are essential in order to counter ‘deficit bias’. The specification of what legislators cannot do (eg increase total spending or reduce total taxes) 
[normal]and can do 
[normal]raises important issues
[normal] of institutional design
[normal]. Nevertheless, their scrutiny role is fundamental to the legitimacy of the budgetary process
[normal] in a democracy
[normal].
[normal]    
[normal] There will be circumstances in which tax expenditures and coerced private expenditures are the most effective policy instrument. The concern here is that they will be over-used and used inappropriately, either because they are not monitored or are difficult to 
[normal]measure
[normal].
[normal] A specific issue is that the United Kingdom has aligned itself to private sector IFRS, with 
[normal]interpretations and 
[normal]adaptations to meet specific public sector circumstances. Paradoxically, though the United Kingdom does not directly follow International Public Sector Accounting Standards (IPSASs), the research study commissioned by Eurostat 
[normal]showed that the
[normal] United Kingdom
[normal] has
[normal] the highest rate of IPSAS compliance among the 
[normal]then EU27
[normal] (Ernst &amp; Young, 2012)
[normal]. This reflects the fact that IPSASs are themselves derived from IFRS. An open question is the extent to which the proposed EPSASs will derive from
[normal] IPSAS or start from a different point. Unless the situation is carefully monitored, the United Kingdom could find itself non-compliant with EPSASs, or have to adopt accounting practices it believes inferior to its present practices, or engage in complicated reconciliations. 
[normal] Possible other names would be ‘Budget Committee’ or ‘Finance Committee’ but I prefer the explicit ‘Spending and Tax Committee’, a name that would clearly communicate its role.
[normal] Its remit should include 
[normal]surrogates
[normal] for public expenditure such as
[normal] off-
[normal]budget expenditures, 
[normal]tax expenditures
[normal], 
[normal]coerced private expenditures, and unrecorded future liabilities 
[normal](Heald, 2012
[normal], pp. 43-4
[normal]).
